NAME: Club A Steakhouse
DESCRIPTION: Established in 2008. Bruno Selimaj was born and raised in a small village on the Northern Albanian/Montenegrin border and began his life as simple farmer. But at the tender age of 18 and with his parents blessing, he embarked on a journey to America in search of new life. In an Albanian household, it is tradition that a guest is treated with the utmost respect and as a member of the family. Bruno brought these core family values to his restaurant and Bruno Selimaj's life defines true restaurant hospitality. In December 2007, Bruno closed his legendary restaurant after 30 years with a new idea and a continuing passion to strive to be the best. He re-opened his famed restaurant as Club A, a modern American steakhouse in the same location. His new venture manages to encompass the characteristics of a traditional steakhouse and new world modernism. His latest accomplishment has established Bruno as one of New York's legendary restaurateurs.

The towering burger creations and frenzy of hot dog toppings speak to the Kings of Kobe core: unadulterated, delicious fun. With utmost attention to quality and harmony of taste, Kings of Kobe ensures a one-of-a-kind experience first and foremost through its food – each dish notable for its mosaic of toppings and succulent base made of domestically sourced Wagyu. And secondly, through its inviting beautiful spaces. Kings of Kobe only ever strives for the best, continuously keeping customers on their toes with unique takes on America American classics. Because food should never be so serious — only boldly delicious.

NAME: Girl & The Goat
DESCRIPTION: Girl & the Goat has been serving fun foods, craft beers, and making wine in a rustic and kick-butt environment since summer 2010. The restaurant opens at 4:30 every day, and stays open until 11pm on weeknights and until midnight on Fridays and Saturdays (until those last late night eaters scrape their fork across the plate for the last time, or finish licking their plates until they're shiny and clean). The Goat's menu is divided into three categories: Vegetable, Fish, and of course Meat--while vegetable, fish, or meat are respectively the main stars of their categories, there are crossovers in each area so you'll get a little bit of everything. Bread is baked daily, and there are always new creations on the menu. Girl & the Goat sits in the West Loop smack dab in the Randolph Restaurant Corridor, but the location is still gritty enough to appeal to the chef’s integrity. The Goat has a variety of seating choices, including a comfortable lounge, bar seats, standard table seating, and four seats close enough to the kitchen line that you might be asked to help.Girl & the Goat blended their own wine, and it's tasty. There are beers on tap from Three Floyd’s and a couple others. If you're lucky, you might come across the elusive collaboration beers that Stephanie personally crafted with a couple of beer buddy cohorts. In addition to tap beers, there's also a bunch of bottles to choose from. Girl & the Goat is open 7 days a week, because The Goat is a tireless beast, and besides, who needs rest anyway? Girl & the Goat accepts reservations but always welcomes walk-ins, nomads, adventurers, and those of you who don’t like to plan.

DESCRIPTION: The Steak House has recently been named Top Las Vegas Steak House by Zagat. The Steak House has been thrilling diners with it's top grade meats served by a friendly, gracious staff for over 36 years. The Steak House also features a glass enclosed dry aging locker. Top grade Midwestern beef is aged for 21 days at 37 degrees Fahrenheit & 67 percent relative humidity. NAME: Sam's Grill And Seafood Restaurant
DESCRIPTION: Sam’s Grill, the fifth-oldest restaurant in the US, opened in 1867, shortly after the California gold rush. Its first location was in the old California Market, an open-air food emporium located where the Bank of America building stands now. Sam’s takes pride in serving exceptionally fresh and local seafood alongside classic San Francisco dishes from the turn of the century. Boasting old-school curtained booths, and superior traditional formal service by waiters in tuxedos, Sam’s has been a cornerstone of the San Francisco restaurant scene for over 150 years. Come join us, and take a step back in time to a more civilized era where lunches always begin with a cocktail. Start with local oysters on the half shell, clams Elizabeth with garlic, butter, and sherry wine, or classic Celery Victor. Coquille Saint Jacques, with mushrooms in cream sauce, and lobster Thermador are two of our favorite classic entrees. Finish with bourbon pecan pie or tiramisu.

NAME: Anchor Oyster Bar
DESCRIPTION: Founded in 1977, Anchor Oyster Bar is a small, locally-owned legacy seafood restaurant and fish market in the Castro serving sustainably-caught fish, shellfish, crab, oysters, and specially prepared seafood dishes, including its signature cioppino dish, which was beautifully described in a New York Times article in May of 2022. Located on Castro Street between 18th and 19th streets, the restaurant occupies a small storefront with a large plate glass window and trademark blue awning, with an intimate interior characterized by linoleum floors, a long white marble bar, chrome chairs, and a daily specials board. Anchor Oyster Bar has been owned and operated by Roseann Grimm for its entire 45-year history. Grimm attributes her love and knowledge of seafood to her grandfather, Nicola Desimone, a fisherman from Amalfi, Italy who worked on salmon and crab boats in North Beach and who opened a seafood market and oyster bar in the neighborhood during the turn of the 20th century.

NAME: Fonda San Miguel
DESCRIPTION: Fonda San Miguel is recognized as one of the finest interior Mexican restaurants in the country, having garnered national and international attention for more than 35 years. Chef Miguel Ravago’s menu of classic regional Mexican cuisine prepared with authentic recipes and ingredients has made the menu offerings and the Sunday Hacienda Brunch Buffet legendary. Considered by many as “Austin’s most beautiful restaurant,” owner Tom Gilliland’s collection of museum-quality artwork, exotic plants, and international décor complete the exquisite dining experience. The restaurant pioneered “interior Mexican” cuisine in the U.S. being one of the first in the nation to introduce the full-flavored and more complex specialties from Mexico’s interior regions. Fonda San Miguel is a celebration of this distinctive cuisine, its colorful history, and the transforming influence it has had on Mexican restaurants across the country.

NAME: 1886 Cafe & Bakery
DESCRIPTION: In the citizen-owned era, The Heritage Society founded the 1886 Lunchroom, successfully operated and staffed for over 20 years by members. Stocked with recipes from the hotel's past (including a stint by Neiman Marcus culinary director and "duchess of Texas cuisine" Helen Corbitt), and their own family histories, the ladies of the Heritage Society operated a venue that to this day is known as "Austin's socializing parlor." Paying homage to the city and Heritage Society's roles, the 1886 Café & Bakery opened on July 4, 2002. Today, located on 6th Street in downtown Austin, the 1886 Café & Bakery remains a respected establishment and favorite bakery for many. The quaint Victorian-style café serves up delicious traditional Texas comfort foods that combine time-honored original recipes with contemporary preparation. Dine on dishes such as Helen Corbitt's Cheese Soup, our famous Texas Shaped Pecan Waffle and Quiche Lorraine, or a bonafide Texas classic, Fried Chicken Sandwich.

DESCRIPTION: Monkeypod Kitchen by Merriman is a place where foodies, beer lovers, and families escape the stresses of their day-to-day lives by enjoying an ice-cold beer and a great meal while surrounded by people who consider them honored guests and friends. NAME: Cho Cho San
DESCRIPTION: Restaurateurs Sam Christie and Jonathan Barthelmess are excited to announce the opening of their new joint venture, Cho Cho San, an interpretation of the Tokyo izakaya. Building on a successful partnership that began with celebrated Potts Point restaurant, The Apollo, Christie and Barthelmess's next project is an exploration of Japanese food culture. Together they will bring free-thinking and a creative approach to the traditions and heritage of Japanese cuisine. As Chef and Co-owner, Barthelmess is developing an ever-changing, seasonal menu keeping to the Japanese philosophy of simplicity where ingredients are the stars. Joined by Head Chef Nicholas Wong working together the focus will be fresh food and healthy eating, using hibachi grilling and steaming techniques. Cho Cho San has created an inventive drinks offering that draws on Japanese drinking traditions reflective of Christie's pioneering experience matching wine with Asian food. "We love the amazing drinking culture in Japan: the tiny bars, the buzzing izakayas and the huge variety of drinks with their deep traditions," he says. "So we've sourced the best sake, shochu, whisky, beer, and a wine list perfectly tailored to suit the food." A small, punchy cocktail menu will change seasonally, drawing on ingredients suchas melon, yuzu, apples, nashi pears and seaweed. Designer George Livissianis once again joins to create a simple, light space that feels Japanese without the cliches or kitsch.

NAME: Poderi Crisci
DESCRIPTION: WelcomePoderi Crisci Vineyard and Winery, set in a stunning amphitheatre surrounded by vines and olive trees, has fast become the quintessence of what in Italy is called: Agroturismo. Located 30 minutes from Matiatia in Awaawaroa Bay, Poderi Crisci occupies 7.7 hectares of north-facing slopes in the heart of Waiheke’s unique wine growing microclimate. The narrow rocky strip underlying Poderi Crisci is believed to be 30 million years older than the rest of the Island, boasting soil criss-crossed with mineralised veins. For four generations the Crisci family has been immersed in food and wine, Antonio born and raised in Napoli came to NZ in early 1990 and established Toto Restaurant in Nelson Street . With his partner Vivienne Farnell they opened Non Solo Pizza, an institution in Parnell in 1997 and Bar Vino in 2009.

NAME: The Riverhead
DESCRIPTION: Dine on the deck this in summer with pleasant views overlooking the water. Our 'Landing Restaurant' offers delicious meals exceeding the expectations of a semi-rural tavern, served with iconic kiwi hospitality. Nestled on the shores of the upper Waitemata, The Riverhead is steeped in local history and was a vital part of the development of early New Zealand. Prior to The Riverhead being built on this site, Thomas Deacon, the original owner, owned a pub on the point just below where The Riverhead now stands. The early Maori used this landing point as the place to disembark and portage their waka across land to the Kumeu River to get easier access to the lands in the Far North. Early immigrants then used this same route to travel north, disembarking at Helensville and continuing by ship north via the Kaipara Harbour.

NAME: Casa Coupage
DESCRIPTION: Learn about the breadth of Argentine wine with a sommelier as your guide. Casa Coupage is a unique space where you can discover & interpret wine paired with delicious argentinian modern food in a truly personal atmosphere. Casa Coupage offers an haute-cuisine venue for Argentine as well as international patrons. “The wine is a noble beverage that reaches its best expression when shared. That’s why we created an exclusive meeting point where a personal relationship with the wine can be developed, together with people who share the same passion”. - Santiago Mymicopulo. The concept itself is irresistibly delicious: dinner is held in a charming dining room of a late 19th century house. NAME: Nuestro Secreto
DESCRIPTION: A major social event in Argentina, the asado (an open-fire barbecue) marks a time when friends and family gather around a traditional outdoor fire pit and spend an afternoon catching up. It is as much about tradition and being together as it is about food. It all begins with the coal; made from hand-picked woods of local tree varietals, each one providing a unique flavour. Cooking whole animals is quite common at the asado, but there is always plenty of variety to choose from - embutidos, meats, red wine and salads. With a casual eclectic backyard esthetic, Nuestro Secreto transports guests to a "secret garden" urban retreat within a bustling cityscape. Typical courtyard decorations abound, with porous stone floors, the grill and clay oven, even a cross on the wall. Outdoor-style furniture made of wood, glass and iron lends an antique but fresh look. All of the tableware is made locally in Mendoza, with exclusive designs by Aji Diseno available for special occasions. What is most unique about this space, however, is that the roof and walls are made of glass and can be opened to create an entirely al fresco space, perfect for stargazing on clear nights. Our Sunday menu features a variety of dishes typically served among families on the weekend. And since our menu is designed to resemble the most-read newspaper in Buenos Aires, it will look to passersby like restaurant patrons are all relaxing with the Sunday paper.
GENERAL_LOCATION: Posadas 1086, Four Seasons Hotel Buenos Aires, C1011

NAME: Elena
DESCRIPTION: When simplicity is truly authentic, it conveys the superb quintessential spirit of the product. This is what we aimed to create while designing Elena's menu. We place absolute importance on the search to find every impeccable ingredient. Proud believers of the farm-to-table philosophy, our iconic charcuterie and cheese platters - paying homage to the Argentine picada - are locally sourced, carefully selected and coming from the country's best farms. The Argentine beef, a driving influential force throughout the entire menu, undergoes the old method of dry aging the meat, aging the beef properly in a highly controlled environment to provide a steak with the utmost quality where the bursting flavors are concentrated and achieve the perfect texture. We pay tribute to our grandmother's cooking with hearty dishes like pastas and osso buco. Through unconventional cooking techniques using a char-broiler and rotisserie spit grill, our food achieves a distinct ideal consistency. At Elena, we carefully and purposefully have thought out every last detail: from the water which is purified and filtered in house, the bread basket which includes homemade sourdough made from our own starter, the elegant coffee cups, and even down to the best sugar and flour for our coffees accompanying petit four. Elena has its roots deeply entrenched into the heart of the local culinary scene. And, from here, conquers the entire world.
GENERAL_LOCATION: Calle Posadas 1086/88, Four Seasons Hotel Buenos Aires, C1011ABB

NAME: The Grill el Gouna
DESCRIPTION: Nestled in the heart of Kafr El Gouna by the lagoon, "The Grill" offers a large variety of deliciously prepared mezzas; succulent charcoal roasted chicken; savory grilled meat, kofta and quails; super tender and mouth watering fillet; and an array of scrumptious wraps, soups and salads. Alternatively our Vegetarian menu features authentic Aubergine Fattah; fulfilling Pasta Vegetariana; Egyptian lentil soup; and fire roasted vegetables; together with delicious list of well prepared salads. All our meals are served with baskets of our signature freshly baked brick oven bread. Choose from a list of well prepared cocktails, mocktails, wine and beer, and enjoy a scenic lagoon view or a cozy indoors area. The Grill is perfect for large groups and birthday celebrations, as well as intimate evenings. For Egyptian, Mediterranean and Oriental cuisine lovers, this restaurant is a must. NAME: Claro
DESCRIPTION: Chef Ran Shmueli is one of Israel’s most respected veteran chefs , who has led innovative culinary ventures for the last 25 years. Claro (“clear” in Spanish) is chef Shmueli’s first restaurant. Claro is not “just” a restaurant; it’s a place of entertainment, providing an experience that embodies all the knowledge of Shmueli and his staff in hospitality and event planning. It is a relaxed venue for social gathering, offering a warm atmosphere, good music and a superb dining experience. The Kitchen | Med Kitchen - Farm to Table Claro’s Med Kitchen (as in Mediterranean), travels through the Mediterranean countries: Spain, France, Italy, Turkey, Greece, Lebanon and Israel, and is presented in the Shmueli relaxed cooking philosophy. The menu, taking the “Farm to Table” approach, is rich in fruits and vegetables, featuring seasonal products from the best local produce. All other ingredients in the menu such as meat, fish, and olive oil are also based on Israeli products, with the aim of promoting local industry and environmental responsibility. The menu is updated almost daily with emphasis on generous portions and reasonable pricing. Every few weeks a seasonal vegetable is selected and widely featured in many of the dishes.

NAME: Bubba Gump Shrimp Co.
DESCRIPTION: En Bubba Gump Shrimp Co. Cancún nuestro ambiente es familiar, dinámico, divertido y de entretenimiento interactivo. Puedes disfrutar de los más bellos atardeceres en nuestra terraza, una increíble área de juegos para los niños, el mejor servicio y por supuesto el mejor ambiente. Contamos con pantallas para que disfrutes de todos los eventos deportivos con audio en vivo, además siempre te recibiremos con el súper servicio que nos caracteriza. DESCRIPTION: Since 1983 La Dolce Vita Centro has been consistently rated as one of the top restaurants in Cancun, serving fresh seafood and homemade pasta, owned and operated by Tim Savio and Juan J. Casal. Dolce Vita means "Sweet Life" in Italian and that is how an evening here will make you feel. Our loyal clientele highly recommend the award winning signature dish Boquinete Dolce Vita, a local snapper topped with shrimp and mushrooms, enclosed in puff pastry, and served with lobster sauce. Private parking and free valet parking service.

NAME: La Vicenta Cancun

NAME: La Galeria Los Cabos
DESCRIPTION: La Galeria Restaurant, established on October 13th, 1997, is a beloved dining destination nestled in the heart of Cabo San Lucas along the Marina. Over the years, we have earned our reputation as one of the go-to restaurants for both locals and visitors seeking exceptional lunch and dinner experiences. Our culinary journey showcases the vibrant flavors of Baja, fused with a Mexican/Mediterranean concept. We are committed to using only the freshest ingredients, meticulously sourced from the finest farms and towns. Each ingredient is handpicked to ensure that every plate we serve is a testament to quality and flavor. At La Galeria, we understand that a truly memorable dining experience is crafted not only by our talented chefs but also by the freshness and selection of every single ingredient. We take pride in curating a menu that tantalizes the taste buds and leaves a lasting impression on our guests. Step into our restaurant and indulge in the artful combination of Baja's.

NAME: Chamisse
DESCRIPTION: Chamisse is a small family business and a hidden gem in central London with authentic Lebanese food and real tastes from home. Every dish is uniquely prepared and freshly made daily to ensure the dish’s authenticity and are not compromising with quality. It is a great choice to share with your family and friends as the restaurant have a fantastic selection which can accommodate most of your dietary requirements (vegetarian, vegan, meat lovers, halal...) and has an amazing selected choice of Lebanese wines from the Bekaa Valley region but also Lebanese beers, spirits, non-alcoholic alternatives choices and freshly made juices. NAME: The Famous Curry Bazaar
DESCRIPTION: Come and enjoy the very best of traditional Indian cuisine. With extensive menus of Indian dishes and wines from around the world, The Famous Curry Bazaar has something for everyone and everyone's something. Owned by the well-respected "Ahmed Brothers" of East London ,Curry Bazaar is a stunning contemporary decor and relaxed ambiance suited to every occasion, complemented by the finest Indian cuisine. NAME: The Clink Restaurant
DESCRIPTION: The Clink Restaurant at HMP Brixton opened in February 2014 as the third restaurant operated by The Clink Charity in the UK and offers up to 30 prisoners full-time work within the restaurant and kitchen. Prisoners train towards gaining nationally recognised City & Guilds NVQs before returning to their cells at the end of the working day. Upon their release, The Clink Charity helps graduates find employment within the catering and hospitality industry. The restaurant is a flagship example of a unique charitable project that is committed to reducing reoffending rates, in partnership with HMPS. NAME: The Rajdoot
DESCRIPTION: When it comes to Indian cuisine, experience and tradition are of crucial importance. Since 1964, the Rajdoot Restaurant has been serving Marylebone and London with food that benefits from our deep knowledge and love for cooking and eating, and we like to keep our secrets and recipes in the family. The four brothers who run the restaurant to this day are the second generation to have done so, and the Rajdoot's mix of friendly regulars and intrigued newcomers is testament to the success of our menu and atmosphere. The experience of the Rajdoot restaurant extends further than authentic, freshly made-to-order cuisine, however. Our welcoming staff are expertly trained in the food and drink industry, and ensure that all of your needs are taken care of, whether in terms of excellent pairings, interesting specials or any specific requirement of taste or diet. Meanwhile, our team of highly skilled chefs use only the finest ingredients, buying fresh spices, which are meticulously ground and blended by hand, ensuring the utmost in freshness, flavour and aroma in all of our dishes. The Rajdoot draws inspiration from all 22 regions of the wonderful, vibrant country of India - from the Himalayas to the Indian Ocean, and the Arabian Sea to the Bay of Bengal. Though our food varies in its regional influence, it is in each instance characterised by the exquisite aromas, vivid colours and deep, earthy flavours that are so unique to Indian cooking. With plenty of excellent reviews from journalists and happy customers alike, which praise everything from the food and drink to the atmosphere and service, our restaurant is perfect for any occasion - a romantic date, a friendly hangout, a larger party or for a simple family meal. We hope to see you soon among our loyal regulars and frequent new visitors.

NAME: Chiancheria Napoli
DESCRIPTION: Dopo Vairano e Roma arriva finalmente anche a Napoli !! Chiancheria e' Hamburgeria, Stekhouse & Tartare Bar ! Un locale dallo stile metropolitano, una meraviglia nel suo genere con 150 posti a sedere piu' una sala prive' in cantina, dove sono custodite centinaia di etichette selezionate dal nostro sommelier. Ad ogni ora del giorno arde la griglia realizzata ad hoc da Vulcano Gres, in quel di Madrid, unica nel suo genere, capace di esaltare il sapore delle carni come poche! Una Selezione maniacale on the road di una materia prima di eccellenza ed una formazione costante del proprio personale attraverso delle Academy studio dedicate, fanno di Chiancheria una mina vagante della Ristorazione, dove viene rispettata la tradizione della cucina partenopea con uno sguardo rivolto all'innovazione! Le carni saranno quindi protagoniste del menu' ! A partire dall'Hamburger di Fattoria Carpineto. Aperti pranzo e cena 7 su 7 con cucina no-stop! Carnivori... non avete scusanti! Vi aspettiamo

NAME: Tavernetta Colauri
DESCRIPTION: Nel verde del borgo di Santa Croce, tra i Camaldoli e Chiaiano, c'è il posto ideale per vivere una coinvolgente esperienza enogastronomica al riparo dal brusio della città. Siete da Tavernetta Colauri. Il ristorante gestito dal 2007 dai due cugini Rosario e Salvatore dove, oltre ai piatti della tradizione partenopea, rivisitati negli accostamenti e nelle presentazioni, potrete gustare vini pregiati e assaporare specialità di carni, nazionali e internazionali, servite su pietre ollari e pietre di sale rosa dell’Himalaya. I mattoni in tufo, le travi a vista, gli antichi attrezzi contadini affissi alle pareti, le botti in legno e le luci calde vi avvolgeranno in una ricercata e intima atmosfera adatta ad accogliere coppie, famiglie e amici. Qui tutto è scelto con cura, a partire dalle materie prime, spesso a km zero e appartenenti ai presidi Slow Food (prodotti rari ed eccellenti), con cui lo chef Rosario Morra prepara ogni giorno piatti raffinati e prelibati.
GENERAL_LOCATION: Via Comunale Margherita, 245, Nei pressi piazza Santa Croce, 80145

NAME: Pur' - Jean-Francois Rouquette
DESCRIPTION: Niché au sein du Park Hyatt Paris-Vendôme, palace contemporain de la Place Vendôme, PUR’ est le restaurant multi-récompensé de Jean-François Rouquette. Avec une étoile Michelin et 17,5 au Gault & Millau, il y propose une approche délicate et instinctive de la gastronomie française. Très expérientiel, PUR’ – JEAN-FRANCOIS ROUQUETTE propose de vivre le ballet d’une brigade le temps d’un dîner à la carte, en 6 ou en 9 services. Depuis la rotonde ou confortablement installé sur les épaisses banquettes tendues de velours clair, le restaurant promet une vue imprenable sur sa majestueuse cuisine ouverte. En rejoignant la « Table du chef » (4 à 6 convives), d’aucuns s’offrent l’exclusivité de l’avant-scène, avec un accès exceptionnel à la création culinaire. Toujours très conviviale, l’ambiance du restaurant reflète la philosophie de son chef moderne, amoureux des beaux produits, et porté par le partage et la transmission. Chef pâtissier : Narae Kim / Chef sommelier : James Barnett

NAME: Habile.
DESCRIPTION: La couturière et le marmiton. Ça pourrait être un conte d’Andersen. C’est juste HABILE. un point c’est tout. Papa pique et maman coud, Éric, c’est le chef, Camille, c’est le patron. Un beau roman, une belle histoire, une romance d’aujourd’hui, ils se sont rencontrés sur l’autoroute du kif et ne l’ont jamais quittée. À l’angle de la rue de Lancry et de la rue du Château d’Eau, HABILE. est une maison à leur image. Un restaurant, d’abord. Un endroit où l’on fait à manger pour restaurer, pour faire du bien, pour faire le bien. Trois ingrédients, bons, propres et durables, trois fois tout plutôt que trois fois rien. Et qu’il se passe quelque chose dans l’assiette, que l’ennui tombe. Betterave, framboise, noisette, chouchou indétrônable, ou chou-fleur, croûton, citron, ça pulse mais ça tient en équilibre. Aller à l’essentiel, épurer, toujours se poser la question : « qu’est-ce qu’on enlève pour que ce soit meilleur ? ».

NAME: Restaurant Bieberbau
DESCRIPTION: Bieberbau at Durlacher Str. 15 in Berlin-Wilmersdorf is part of a former studio and dwelling house. Built 1893/94 by Wilhelm Walther for the sculptuor Richard Bieber, it was nearly completely destroyed by a firebomb during World War II. Only the rooms and decoration of what is now the restaurant survived. The stucco ornamentation you can admire here have been created by the most advanced students and trainedcraftsmen of the principal and owner. He maintained a plasterer's and sculptuor's studio. The decorations depict different motives from mythology and rural life. They show advanced technical skills. The premises in their organic design provide an insight into the stuccateurs' craftmenship unique for Berlin around the turn of the twentieth century. They offer a unique spatial experience the qualitiy and complexitiy of which were out of the ordinary. In the backyard of the house there were several studios, amongst others those of the expressionist work group ,,Die Brücke" (,,The Bridge"). Between 1910 and 1913 Max Pechstein and Ernst Ludwig Kirchner worked here.

NAME: India Club
DESCRIPTION: The INDIA CLUB Restaurant serves an authentic north indian cuisine, that claims to be best in Germany. Head chef Manish Bahukhandi is one of the most striking representatives of the indian “rustic cuisine” and had last cooked at the 5 Star Hotel “The Claridges” in New-Delhi. He has been engaged in the indian top restaurants and hotels like “The Oberoi” in New-Delhi and the “Taj Mount Road” in Chennai. He will bring his hand selected team of specialty chefs: one for Curry dishes and another one for Tandooris. Fundamental for the indian cuisine are the authentic Tandoor-oven made from clay, where bread, meat and vegetables are cooked. Following the traditionally indian cuisine, INDIA CLUB will renounce on beef and pork but we therefor offer chicken, lamb, duck, fish and seafood. Poultry and lamb are from highest organic quality, and humane treatment of animals. They exclusively come from our agricultural Gut Vorder Bollhagen of the Jagdfeld family near the Baltic Sea.

NAME: YOSOY Tapas Bar
DESCRIPTION: Welcome to "YOSOY" the Spanish Tapas-Bar in Berlin Mitte. Tapas strongly belong to the daily life in Spain and contain all the small appetizing cold and warm spanish food from which we are offering a choice. The origin of Tapas lies in Andalusia and is closely connected with a GLASS of sherry or wine. One says that the piece of bread, the slice of ham or the cheese which was put as a "lid" on the sherry or wineglass, was put around to retain the strange aroma in the GLASS, that's the origin of the Tapa-culture in Spain. In addition, the pleasure and the way of life came naturally to lean against a bar and to talk to friends, strangers, the family or the landlord of this and that having a small lunch and a glass of sherry or wine and lose the whole time of the day. Hopefully, we have created such a comfortable place with our Tapas-Bar.

NAME: Caravin Wine & Wanderlust
DESCRIPTION: The Wine Caravan. Two women with passion for wine, travel and adventure, meet and their vision takes shape. We are Leoni and Anna, two women with passion for wine, travel and adventure. Through our page we would like to project our vision and our love for unpretentiously nice food of our place and our aesthetics for life. NAME: Arcano Barcelona
DESCRIPTION: Situated near Barcelona's bustling main streets, Arcano is a culinary gem housed in a charming 17th-century building. What sets us apart is our dedication to the art of charcoal oven cooking. This ancient method infuses each dish with a distinctive smoky flavor that leaves a lasting impression. Our menu is a celebration of this tradition, featuring a diverse range of dishes. From the crispness of fresh vegetables to the tenderness of succulent meats and the delicacy of perfectly prepared fish, every bite tells a story of craftsmanship and flavor. As you explore the vibrant streets of Barcelona, don't miss the opportunity to experience this unique culinary journey. Arcano promises not just a meal, but a taste of history and tradition.

NAME: The Venue Steak House
DESCRIPTION: The Venue's notion is simple: old school elegant dishes using the finest ingredients prepared by our top chefs. The deceptively easy dishes earn their place with the choicest cuts of meat imported from Ireland. The vibe? Grown up, relaxed, playful. The setting? An opulent room you'll feel at home in, only better. In how many places can you get a perfectly cooked rib-eye steak with immaculate flavour, crisp triple cooked chunky chips? Notice the words "perfectly" and "immaculate". No, there are not many restaurants with the courage to deliver a menu based on the very sound theory that less is more; that a good kitchen is much better off cooking steak rather than mucking around with all manner of fashionable, cheffy malarkey. So, we take our hats off to our fantastic team, for helping us bring The Venue Sreakhouse to Barcelona. Come and join us at The Venue where there's always a warm welcome!

NAME: Miku
DESCRIPTION: Miku Vancouver, a Michelin Guide Recommended restaurant, specializes in Aburi, or flamed-seared, sushi, which was developed nearly a century ago in Japan. The act of applying fire directly to sushi enhances the natural flavors and textures of the fish, creating a new and exciting culinary experience. Miku owner Seigo Nakamura innovated the Aburi concept by crafting specialty sauces using non-traditional Japanese ingredients to pair with each type of fish. The light sear from the binchotan (Japanese bamboo charcoal) caramelizes the sauce, releasing a smoky aroma and bringing out the finest flavors in each piece of Aburi sushi. Miku Restaurant is within walking distance from the Pan Pacific Hotel, Canada Place, Fly Over Canada, Cruise Ship Terminals, and Sea Bus.
GENERAL_LOCATION: 70-200 Granville St, Corner of Canada Place and Howe St, V6C 1S4

NAME: 1 Kitchen
DESCRIPTION: 1 Kitchen Toronto serves up fresh, local, and sustainably sourced farm-to-table cuisine. The restaurant is a zero-waste operation, which spotlights the team's commitment to preserving the beauty and bounty of nature. And then there's the bar, where cold-pressed juices form the base of cocktails. The wine list highlights unique and iconic selections - many biodynamic or organic - you'll also find handcrafted cocktails and Bluestone Lane coffee. NAME: Sampan - The Sky Lounge
DESCRIPTION: Media Leisure TestimonialHOW TO REACHTemprature: 32 C / 90 FHome> Sampan, New DelhiDiscover the true flavours of Asia at the all new SampanIt’s a sight to behold the moment you step inside Sampan at The Suryaa New Delhi. A panoramic view of Delhi shining under the stars spellbinds every visitor to this address of authentic Pan Asian cuisine in the heart of South Delhi. As you walk in you are greeted by a small cluster of tall Bamboo plants. The impressive interior of the restaurant is ready to cast its spell on you. The rich wooden texture on the walls and ceilings are highlighted by Oriental style custom crafted artifacts. Chinese letters are cleverly used as motifs at the open kitchen and the entrance door.The dim yet clever lighting adds an ethereal charm to the entire space. 3 different seating arenas, the formal table set up, the luxurious lounge seating with couches and sofas and a discrete private dining area would again amaze you with their contemporary elegance.While the ambience eases you with its warmth, the vast selection of popular and not-so-well-known culinary treasure promises an unforgettable experience. The new menu is dotted with the best from China in terms of remarkable Cantonese, bold Sichuan, traditional Mandarin, new-age Shanghai and Beijing cuisines. The South-East Asian section offers lesser known jewels from Myanmar like the delicious Monhinga, Mandalay curries and the Panthé. The Thai selection is extensive with robust Massamans, the hung lay from north and the Penang style seafood and commercial styles from Bangkok. Relish the East Asia with Vietnamese Popiah, Indonesian Sambals, Malay Rojak and the Japanese Hitoku with the universally popular Singaporean chilli crabs. The Japanese selection is an aesthetic collection of Ceviche style Sashimi, Chirashi sushi, Hina Matsuri Bentou, Tendon to a Macha-Misu. The teppan station plays a host to skilled chefs tossing anything from Foie gras, Prawn Cabrera to Uzura quails apart from the Somen and the Udons. A range of exclusive seafood like a Halibut, Black Cod, Scallops, and Blue Fin Tuna has been incorporated to occupy a pride of place.The show kitchen houses a versatile dumpling steamer to dole out scrumptious Har Gaws, Sui Mai, Bao and Tibetan momos. A duck rotisserie is now a part of the fleet to dish out a heavenly Beijing duck for the connoisseurs. A live sushi counter is another feather in the cap. To add a Delhi touch to the truly oriental fare, a dedicated page on ‘Local favourites’, a fusion of Chinese and local flavours, has been included to serve the local palate.
GENERAL_LOCATION: The Suryaa Hotel, 12th Floor, New Friends Colony, The Suryaa Hotel, New Friends Colony, 110065

NAME: Cai Mam Vietnamese Restaurant 2
DESCRIPTION: From north to south, from urban to rural areas of Vietnam, Cai Mam" is a very familiar object. For each family, "Cai Mam" appears twice in everyday; at lunch and at dinner. "Cai Mam" is a round tray used to contain objects, especially food. In the past, "Cai Mam" was made of wood. Today, the majority of "Cai Mam" trays are made of aluminum or stainless steel. During a meal, everyone in the family gather round “Cai Mam" with various and delectable food. It is the time for the family to care of each other, to share and to show solidarity. An indispensable cultural feature of Vietnamese tradition; at each "meal invitation", before eating, younger people invite the elders to show their deep gratitude with appreciation of the parents. Meanwhile, elders will nod affectionately, and the whole family will begin a meal in a fun atmosphere. What could be more touching than a New Year dinner, people reuniting with loved ones around the familiar "Cai Mam", and enjoy tasty homeland dishes.
GENERAL_LOCATION: 23 Đào Duy Từ, Hàng Buồm, Hoàn Kiếm

NAME: Colony
DESCRIPTION: Located on level three of The Ritz-Carlton, Millenia Singapore, the name Colony alludes to the seafarious voyage that the British took to travel to the East Indies for trade and commerce in the late eighteenth century. Vintage maps and postcards which adorn the walls and decorative ornate leafing evoke the nostalgia of a bygone era, while eight different open concept kitchens, coupled with 'live' culinary showmanship, will bring diners on a multi-sensory journey through Singapore's heritage cuisines including Malaysian, Indonesian, Indian, Chinese and Western, with dishes that reflect the flavours of the nation's rich colonial past. Colony can seat a maximum of 260 persons and boasts a dynamic space that can be configured to accommodate groups of various sizes. The restaurant will offer breakfast, lunch, afternoon tea and dinner daily, and vintage Champagne brunch on Sundays.

DESCRIPTION: Housed at the summit of ION Orchard under 1-ATICO's roof, FLNT is the only lifestyle destination for Nikkei culture in Singapore. NAME: Cherry Garden
DESCRIPTION: Cherry Garden offers an eclectic menu of Cantonese cuisine, presented with artistic modern flair. Entering via a striking antique doorway, the restaurant has been designed according to Feng Shui. Charcoal teak panels and slate floors recreate the look of a splendid Oriental residence. Using fresh, seasonal produce, the menu features authentic Cantonese dishes. A varied wine list features a balanced selection of old and new world wines specially selected to match the menu. NAME: Parc
DESCRIPTION: Mama knows best! PARC was founded in 2013 in the Hannam district of Seoul, which is the most international neighborhood of Korea's capital city. PARC, which translates to park in the famed romance language of Catalan, serves traditional Korean food inspired from authentic family recipes by owner Pak Mogua's mother, Heo Junghee, that have been passed down through generations of family. After 4 years of traveling the world, Pak realized the strong impact his mother's cooking had always had on him with its unique and genuine flavors. It was then when he decided to collect all of his mother's recipes to not only document for himself, but to also share with people he loved. In the summer of 2012, co-owners Pak Mogua and Oo Zeemin came up with the idea for PARC while sitting in what would eventually become the actual restaurant space. They designed PARC to be casual and affordable, and a friendly restaurant where everyone is welcome and can dine in comfort. PARC prides itself on serving authentic and homemade Korean dishes using the freshest ingredients with both modern and traditional cooking techniques. With a seasonal menu featuring the best of Korean cuisine, we hope you come and try our Korean Mother's Recipes & More. "Parc is my favourite restaurant in Seoul." -Sophie Hicks (Architect, London, UK dined more than 3 times) "This is very warm energy you have here." -Toni Alva (Legenday Skater, CA, USA dined twice)

NAME: Gyukatsu Motomura Harajuku
DESCRIPTION: Very popular "Gyukatsu" (beef cutlet) restaurant that now runs 6 branches in Tokyo (as of October 2016). Note that Shibuya branches are always very crowded and you should expect to wait for an hour or so, I'd suggest you get there 30-60 minutes prior or go to the other branches (less crowded). The beef cutlet is deep-fried outside very quickly, so it's fairly rare inside. It used to be more cooked and you were to eat it as is, but as they became popular among visitors from overseas, they started serving a stone grill along with the cutlet so that you can cook as you like. I imagine there was an increasing feedback from the customers that the meat was too rare. I actually liked more the way it used to be, but guess it's better now for non-Japanese customers. It's 1,300 JPY (130g of beef) and comes as a combo and the photo abve is 2,100 JPY combo (260g of beef). I'd say 130g would be enough for most people.

NAME: Gyukatsu Ichi Ni San
DESCRIPTION: Very popular "Gyukatsu" (beef cutlet) restaurant that now runs 6 branches in Tokyo (as of October 2016). Note that Shibuya branches are always very crowded and you should expect to wait for an hour or so, I'd suggest you get there 30-60 minutes prior or go to the other branches (less crowded). The beef cutlet is deep-fried outside very quickly, so it's fairly rare inside. It used to be more cooked and you were to eat it as is, but as they became popular among visitors from overseas, they started serving a stone grill along with the cutlet so that you can cook as you like. I imagine there was an increasing feedback from the customers that the meat was too rare. I actually liked more the way it used to be, but guess it's better now for non-Japanese customers. NAME: Kyoto Gion Tempura Endo Yasaka Honten
DESCRIPTION: For over 130 years, Endo has been welcoming guests to its restaurants on the historical and atmospheric streets of Gion, Kyoto. Originally founded as an ochaya teahouse where geisha would perform, we have honored that heritage and status while also continuing to innovate. Endo has embraced new styles and is always striving for new levels of culinary excellence. Just beyond the precincts of Kennin-ji, one of Japan's oldest Zen temples, our main restaurant lies hidden away on tranquil Yasaka-dori in the backstreets of Gion, overlooked auspiciously by Gojunoto Five-Storied Pagoda. Traditional Kyoto vegetables, wild herbs, fresh seafood from Wakasa Bay and the Seto Inland Sea, freshwater fish from the clear streams that run into Lake Biwa… Enjoy Endo's legendary Kyoto-style tempura, prepared fresh to order with an ever-changing cornucopia of seasonal, local produce.

NAME: Mozambik V & A Waterfront
DESCRIPTION: With its roots firmly set in passion and its flavours unapologetically Afro Porto, the Mozambik restaurant group is fast becoming one of South Africa’s leading dining brands. From its launch as a single store in Ballito, Kwa-Zulu Natal circa 15 years ago, the brand has seen rapid growth over the past half-decade, now totaling 18 stores nationally. Later in 2019, the Mozambik brand will also expand north of the Limpopo with its first international store scheduled to open in Lusaka. Chef Brett Michelien has, over time, developed a range of bastings, sauces and rubbing spices that has become Mozambik’s trademark. The menu is inspired by Afro-Porto cuisine with a rich tapestry of flavour the common denominator across an eclectically styled offering. From traditional fare such as prawns through to Mozambik’s famous chicken, the menu offers a wide variety of taste experiences.

NAME: Ben's on the Beach
DESCRIPTION: Situated on the beachfront in the Strand, Ben's on the Beach boasts spectacular views across False Bay, towards Cape Town. Veteran award-winning restaurateur Ben, and his wife, Shirley (a former hotel school lecturer), established Ben's in 2004. They have created a stylish yet relaxed venue, where a varied and well-priced selection of dishes is offered. Ben's is one of the few remaining establishments that continues to dry-age meat - the time-honored and superior method. At Ben's you will not find over-priced and under-portioned "haute cuisine". We believe that the new expression "less is more" is gobbeldygook, where food is concerned. We concentrate on the simple yet timeless dishes that diners return to again and again, such as a great steak, fresh linefish, and the ever-popular creme brulee. At Ben's, you will discover generous portions at honest prices. We look forward to your visit ... And then return!
